UAB, 16-18 June, 2021

A simple example of unconfoundedness

Unconfoundedness and Controlling for confounders

  • Under the Unconfoundedness (aka Conditional Independance) assumption

\[ \small \{Y_{i}(1), Y_{i}(0)\} \perp D_i | {X}_i \]

  • We block backdoor paths that create noncausal correlations

Identification of conditional ATE and of ATE

  • Consider the difference of conditional expectations \[ \small E[Y |{x}, D = 1] - E [Y |{x}, D = 0] = E[Y(1) |{x}, D = 1] - E [Y(0)|{x}, D = 0] \]

  • Under unconfoundedness, \[ \small \begin{align*} E[Y(1) |{x}, D = 1] &=E[Y(1) |{x}, D = 0] = E[Y(1) |{x}] \\ E[Y(0) |{x}, D = 1] &=E[Y(0) |{x}, D = 0] = E[Y(0) |{x}] \end{align*} \]

  • Hence,

\[ \small \begin{align*} E[Y |{x}, D = 1] - E [Y |{x}, D = 0] &= E[Y(1) |{x}] - E [Y(0)|{x}] \\ &= E[Y(1)-Y(0)|{x}] = ATE({x}) \end{align*} \]

  • These conditional expectations, \(E [Y |{x}, D ]\), depend entirely on observables

  • Then \(\small ATE= E_X[ATE(X)]\)

Unconfoundedness and “selection on observables”

  • Under uncoundoundedness, we assume that differences between the treated and the control group can be explained by \(\small {x}\)

    • given these characteristics, treatment status is random.

  • It implies selection into treatment operates only through \(\small {x}\)

    • Either characteristics directly determine participation

    • or individuals with different characteristics have different potential outcomes (which determine participation)

Unconfoundedness is untestable

  • Unconfoundedness is only satisfied when conditioning on all the relevant variables

    • So, treated and control individual are really comparable/similar

  • Researchers should convince that conditioning on their set of particular characteristics is “enough”

  • Note that there are always missing variables, but we are worried about those related to treatment status and potential outcomes.

Estimation of Treatment Effects

  • We will see three “different” approaches to estimate ATE under unconfoundedness

    • Regression

    • Weighting (based on Propensity Score)

    • Matching

  • Similarities are more than differences: all of them share main basic assumption, plus other minor ones

  • All three types can actually be written as weighting estimators in the literal sense.

Unconfoundedness and regression

  • Under unconfoundedness, it can be prove that

\[ \small E[Y|D, {x}] = \mu_0 + \alpha D + g_0 ({x})+ D[ g_1 ({x})- g_0 ({x})] \]

  • Under some additional assumptions about parametric functional forms of \(\small g_0 ({x})\) and \(\small g_1 ({x})\), we get the standard (linear) regression model

  • These \(\small g_0 ({x})\) and \(\small g_1 ({x})\) are functions that controls for the selection bias

  • Under unconfoundedness, selection bias is a “known” function of observables: selection on observable

Propensity Score and the Overlap Assumption

  • The propensity score is the probability of treatment given the covariates \({x}\): \[ \small p( {x})= \Pr( D = 1| {X}={x}) \]

  • Overlap (or common support) assumption \[ \small 0 < p({x}) <1, \quad \forall {x} \in supp({X}) \]

    • Each unit in the defined population has some chance of being treated and some chance of being untreated.

  • \(ATT\) is identified with a weaker assumption: \[ \small p({x}) <1, \quad \forall {x} \in supp({X}) \]

    • It can make sense to exclude units that have no chance of being treated: millionaires when evaluating a job training program

Comments on the Overlap Assumption

  • The parametric linear regression model does not require the common support condition: the functional form fills in (extrapolates) for the data that are missing when this assumption fails to hold

  • If common support condition fails we should only be able to identify ATE for the range of values with common support.

  • But if we extrapolate using a bad parametric approximation outside the region we can find spurious positive or negative effects…

  • This is both part of the charm and part of the horror of the standard parametric approach:

The Propensity Score Theorem

  • By conditioning either on \({x}\) or on the propensity score we get rid of the correlation between potential outcomes and \(D\)

    \[ \small (Y(0), Y(1)) \perp D| {x} \quad \Rightarrow (y_0 , y_1) \perp D| p ({x}) \]

  • \(p({x})\) contains all the relevant information in \({x}\) about \(D\), even though it is a particular function of \({x}\) (smaller set)

  • Implication: overlap decreases with the dimensionality of the adjustment set

Pseudo-populations

Inverse Probability Weighting

  • Under unconfoundedness and overlap assumptions

\[ \small \begin{aligned} E\left[\frac{DY}{p({x})}\right]-E\left[\frac{(1-D)Y}{(1-p({x}))}\right] &= E \left[\frac{(D-p({x}))Y}{p({x}) (1-p({x}))}\right] = ATE \\ & \\ \frac{1}{\Pr(D=1)}\left(E\left[DY\right]-E\left[\frac{(1-D)Yp({x})}{(1-p({x}))}\right] \right) &=\frac{1}{\Pr(D=1)}E \left[\frac{(D-p({x}))Y}{(1-p({x}))}\right] \\ &= ATT \end{aligned} \]

  • We need an estimator of the propensity score \(p({x} )\), eg., using a flexible parametric model \[ \small\widehat{p}({x}) \equiv F({x};\widehat{\gamma}) \]

  • Then we obtain consistent estimates of ATE and ATT

The Balancing Condition

  • The propensity score theorem implies that the assignment to treatment is random for individuals with the same propensity score.

  • In other words, if their ex-ante probability of treatment is just the same, their actual status can only be explained by random reasons.

  • Therefore, individuals with the same propensity score should look, on average, identical in terms of their unobservable and observable characteristics in the treatment and in the control group.

  • Note the analogue with experiments: random assignment balanced both observed and unobserved characteristics of the treated and untreated individuals

  • Analyses based on propensity scores should report evidence on balance, just as experimental analyses do.

The Balancing Condition (cont‚Äôd)

  • The simplest test is to compute the IPW formulae for \(X\) after re-weighting: \(\small \widetilde{X}=\frac{DX}{p({x})}+\frac{(1-D)X}{(1-p({x}))}\)

  • Ex.: Kolmogorov-Smirnov test for the distribution of \(\small \widetilde{X}\) (after weighthing), being the same for the treated and the untreated

  • A common measure is based on standardized differences: \[ \small StdDiff=\dfrac{\overline{X}_{1W}-\overline{X}_{0W}}{\sqrt{\left(V_{1W}(X)+V_{0W}(X)\right)}} \]

  • Also the ratio of variances \(V_{1W}(X)/V_{0W}(X)\) should be one.

  • Balance is informative about a potential failure of unconfoundedness (not controlling for all the relevant characteristics), but it may also fails if propensity score specification is not flexible enough.

Matching

  • Matching estimators impute a value on the counterfactual for each unit:

    • Unit \(i\) in the control group: we observe \(Y_{i}(0)\), but need to impute \(Y_{i}(1)\)

    • Unit \(j\) in the treated group: we observe \(Y_{j}(1)\), but need to impute \(Y_{j}(0)\)

  • Matching estimators take the general form: \[ \small \widehat{ATE}_{matching} = \frac{1}{n} \sum^n_{i=1} (\widehat{Y}_{i}(1)-\widehat{Y}_{i}(0)) \] \[ \small \widehat{ATET}_{matching} = \frac{1}{n_1} \sum^n_{i=1} D_i(Y_i-\widehat{Y}_{i}(0)) \]

    • Note that \(Y_{i}(1)\) is always observed for the treated subsample (\(D_i = 1\)), so we never need to impute it.

Matching (cont‚Äôd)

  • The procedure construct imputations of missing potential outcomes by matching treated and untreated individuals on their observable characteristics \(x\)

  • In the discrete case, \(\small \widehat{Y}_{i}(0) = \overline{Y}_0^{j(i)}\equiv \sum_{k\in(D=0)} \frac{1(X_k=X_i)}{\sum_{l\in(D=0)}1(X_l=X_i)}Y_k\)

  • In general, \(\small \widehat{Y}_{i}(0) = \sum_{k\in(D=0)} w(i,k) Y_k\)

    (and similarly for \(\widehat{Y}_{i}(1)\))

  • Different matching estimators use different weighting schemes.

Exact and Inexact Matching

  • Exact matching (or cell matching) is practicable when the vector of covariates is discrete and the sample contains many observations at each distinct value of \({x}_i\)

  • If the covariate vector is highly dimensional and/or some covariates are continuous, exact matching becomes impractical: many cells will have no counterfactual observation.

    • “curse of dimensionality” / common support problem.

  • Inexact matching reduce the dimension of the problem by defining a distance metric on \({x}\) and then matching using the scalar distance \(D({x})\) rather than the vector \({x}\).

  • Asymptotically (and under common support assumption), all inexact matching schemes are equivalent (in large sample, one has only exact matches). But they can yield very different answers in finite samples.

How to Match: Single Match for each observation

  • The simplest approach to find a match (Abadie and Imbens, 2006) is a single match for each observation

  • If \(i\) is a treated unit (\(D_i=1\)), then \(\widehat{y}_{1,i}=Y_i\) and \(\widehat{Y}_{i}(0)=Y_h\)

    • such that \(D_h = 0\)

    • and unit \(h\) is “closest” to unit \(i\) based on some metric (distance) in the covariates (\(x_h\) is “closest” to \(x_i\))

  • For the treated unit \(i\) we find the “most similar” untreated observation \(h\) and use its response as \(Y_{i}(0)\)

  • Procedure is similar if \(i\) is a control unit (\(D_i=0\))

How to Match: Single Match for each observation (cont‚Äôd)

  • Note that the nearest neighbor can be not very similar due to a failure of the common support condition or due to small sample size.

  • The balance condition after match can be checked (ex.: the distribution of characteristics for the treated individuals and their matches should be similar (“common support”))

  • The most popular metrics for distance the between observations \(i\) and \(j\) are the Mahalanobis metric: \[d_M ({x}_i, {x}_j) = ({x}_i - {x}_j )' \Sigma^{-1}_{{x}} ({x}_i - {x}_j )\]

    • where \(\Sigma_{{x}}\) is the covariance matrix of the covariates

How to Match: Several neighbors

  • More generally, we can impute the missing value using an average of \(M\) nearest neighbors

  • If \(i\) is a treated unit (\(D_i=1\)), then \[ \small \widehat{Y}_{i}(1)=Y_i\] and \[\small \widehat{Y}_{i}(0)=\frac{1}{M}\sum_{h\in A^U_M(i) }Y_h\]

    • where \(A^U_M(i)\) contains \(M\) untreated nearest matches to observation \(i\), based on the covariates

    • so \(D_h = 0,\quad \forall h\in A^U_M(i)\)

Matching on the Propensity Score

  • Matching on the propensity score is computationally easier because it is a single variable with range in \((0, 1)\)

  • Intuition: we estimate the counterfactual of individual \(i\) using individual(s) that are similar terms of the propensity score.

  • Why is this appealing?

    • Suppose we select two individuals with the same propensity score: ex-ante they have the same likelihood of treatment

    • One receives treatment and the second does not: ex-post assignment to treatment can be regarded as “random”

  • Note the importance of Overlapping: we need common support of characteristics for the treated and control individuals

Variations on matching

  • Bias-corrected matching (using regression), Abadie and Imbens (2011)

  • Multi-treatment matching (many pairwise comparisons)

  • Matching for continuous treatments (i.e.¬†dose-response: how to discretize the treatment?)

  • Difference-in-differences matching, controlling semi-parametrically for covariates

  • Estimators that enforce balancing (entropy balance)
